05064nam a22007335i 9780823290864DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232908647 a10.1515/97808232908642doi  a(DE-B1597)565932  a(OCoLC)1306539491  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aART0060002bisacsh00aAncient Mediterranean Art :bThe William D. and Jane Walsh Collection at Fordham University /ced. by Jennifer Udell, Barbara Cavaliere. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b352 Illustrations, color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCypriot Art (Nos. 1−3) -- tGreek Art -- tVillanovan, Etruscan, and Italic Art -- tRoman Art -- tCoins -- tAncient Near Eastern Art -- tBibliography -- tAppendix: Illustrated List of Works in the Collection0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAncient Mediterranean Art: The William D. and Jane Walsh Collection at Fordham University is the catalogue of Fordham University’s remarkable collection of Classical antiquities, comprising objects dating from the fourth millennium B.C.E. to the 4th century C.E., originating from Greece, Italy, Turkey, the Near East, and Egypt. It is one of the largest collections of antiquities held by an academic institution in the New York area and includes many important works of ancient Mediterranean art that are published here for the first time. This lavishly illustrated book features 104 of the most significant objects in the William D. and Jane Walsh Collection. All the major art forms from the Greek, Etruscan, and Roman worlds are represented, including pottery, sculpture, glass, architectural decoration, and coins. Each object entry is accompanied by one or more color photographs, some with detailed profile drawings, along with explanatory text examining the individual artistic significance of the pieces; their domestic, religious, civic, or funerary function; and their relationship to objects of similar type published elsewhere and in other museum collections. Interspersed throughout are enlightening thematic essays—for example, on Italic votives and on Etruscan roofs and their decoration—that provide valuable context for the individual objects. An appendix provides a comprehensive list of the works in the collection with brief descriptions and photographs of those not given fuller scholarly attention. The extensive bibliography and notes further augment the value of this catalogue as an educational resource and a notable contribution to the corpus of scholarship about the art, history, and culture of the ancient Mediterranean world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aART / Collections, Catalogs, Exhibitions / General.2bisacsh1 aCavaliere, Barbara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUdell, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUdell, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWalsh, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082324452240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329086440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823290864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823290864/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4 